# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1847-state-of-the-union-address
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The state of union is an address, in the United States, given by the president to a joint session of Congress, the United States House of Representatives and United States Senate.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The United States constitution requires the president "from time to time give to the Congress Information of the State of the Union." Today the state of the union address is given as a speech, though this is not a requirement of the constitution.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] George Washington chose to address the Congress in a speech annually; on October 25, 1791, he gave his third speech.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] A major concern at the time was the raising of taxes, as Congress were arguing whether they had the constitutional power to do so.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Revenues for the Federal Government were at that time mostly collected on import duties.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Alexander Hamilton, the then Secretary of the Treasury, felt these had been raised to as high a level as was reasonable, and a new income stream was necessary.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Before the speech, Congress had been debating where to put the capital.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Finally, through a deal made between Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson, they came to a conclusion.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] This deal is known as the Compromise of 1790.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the U.S. was in possession of the original thirteen colonies, along with the land gained in the Treaty of Paris.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The Treaty of Paris ended the revolutionary war; in it, America was granted territory as far west as the Mississippi River.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Known as the year of "Great Immigration" 1788 was the year many Americans moved west.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On October 18, 1790, the Ohio tribe defeated an expedition of American troops near Fort Wayne, Indiana; this signified the beginning of the hostilities in the North West territory.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On March 30, 1791, construction of the Knoxville Road began, linking to the Wilderness Road and to Knoxville.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The road opened up more frontier area for settlements.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] In September 1791, there was much hostility in Ohio territory; this caused Americans to build forts at Hamilton, St.Clair, Jefferson, Greenville and Recovery.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the Census Act had been in place for just over a year and a half.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The act called for a routine census of the United States, and was passed by Congress on March 1, 1790.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He acknowledged that there had been some "degree of discontent" about the Whiskey Tax, and that it was not perfect, but he was going to keep it anyway.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He said "revision of the provision will be found advisable." The Whiskey tax was one Hamilton wanted enacted as part of a funding system for the new country.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the debt has been mostly dealt with, but there might be a few things that still need to be paid off and he urges the House of Representatives to pay off any lingering debts, and there will be exact numbers coming to them soon.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] "The part of the debt of the United States which remains unsubscribed will naturally engage your further deliberation," Washington is saying the House of Representatives must talk further on the debt that has not yet been dealt with.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington briefly mentions the "completion of the census of the inhabitants," he is talking about the Census of 1790.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that "the present population of the United States borders on 4,000,000 persons".
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The number was 3,929,625 according to the 1790 Census.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the end of the speech he comments on "the militia, the post office and post roads, the mint, weights and measures, a provision for the sale of the vacant lands of the United States." Washington wants to send militia to particularly vulnerable places in the US, as they are a new country.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the United States must have "systematic and solid arrangements, exposed as little as possible to the hazards of fortuitous circumstances." He beliefs that there must be more post offices and roads, to create unity with in the country.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] As well to make sure that there is no :misrepresentation and misconception" of the "laws and proceedings of the Government." He then remarks that there is a scarcity of smaller American change and that there must be more put into place.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington then goes on to say that the wright and measures of the country must be uniform and conducive to public convenience.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington spent a good deal of the speech trying to convince the Native Americans to become part of the United States, as well as convincing the citizens of the country of the importance of doing so.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He pushed the Senate to ratify the treaties pending before that House with the Cherokees and Six Nations of Indians (Iroquois Confederation).
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He stated that the House needed to act on bills to ensure the financial security of the nation.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The **1792 State of the Union Address** was delivered by George Washington to Congress on Tuesday, November 6, 1792.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented in Philadelphia's Congress Hall.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The president commented on continued incursions by Native Americans into frontier settlements.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Notably, the address contains mention of the Chickamaugas, a part of the Cherokee tribe that committed multiple incursions in frontiers along the Tennessee River.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The President noted that the incursions were a violation of the Treaty of Holston.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Still further to promote and secure these inestimable ends there is nothing which can have a more powerful tendency than the careful cultivation of harmony, combined with a due regard to stability, in the public councils.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The **1793 State of the Union Address** was given by George Washington, the first president of the United States.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] It was given in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at Congress Hall.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] During the address, Washington spoke of Peace through strength.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] He also urged the expansion of the legal code and jurisdiction of the courts in order to enforce the laws of the land.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The President reported on progress for peace with the Creek and Cherokee tribes and noted that trade with the tribes should be expanded where possible.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] The **1794 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the first president of the United States, George Washington, to a joint session of the 3rd United States Congress on November 19, 1794.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] The speech came in the aftermath of the Whiskey Rebellion, an armed insurrection in the western counties of Pennsylvania against the federal excise tax on whiskey.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] Washington highlighted the failure of peaceful measures, noting that the government's attempts at moderation and reconciliation were misinterpreted as weakness.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] He described how, despite offering pardons and seeking negotiations, the insurrection continued, leading to the deployment of 15,000 militia troops.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] The address also stressed the importance of upholding the Constitution, warning against the dangers posed by lawlessness and sedition.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] Washington praised the militia for their dedication and perseverance, remarking on the "patriotic cooperation" between the federal government and the states.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] In addition to addressing the Whiskey Rebellion, Washington briefly touched upon other issues, including relations with Native American tribes and the nation's foreign policy, particularly the need to avoid entanglements in European conflicts.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] The **1795 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the first president of the United States, George Washington, to a joint session of the 4th United States Congress on December 8, 1795.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] This address covered a broad range of topics, including foreign relations, military affairs, and the domestic state of the Union.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] Washington began by celebrating the peace agreement made with the Native American tribes north of the Ohio River, known as the Treaty of Greenville, ending a long and costly war.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He emphasized that the satisfaction of the tribes had been a key objective of the treaty to ensure lasting tranquility.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] Additionally, Washington discussed ongoing peace negotiations with Algiers and the recognition of the United States' treaty by the Emperor of Morocco.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He also noted the progress of negotiations with Spain and the recently signed Jay Treaty with Great Britain.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] Washington praised the economic prosperity of the nation, highlighting the rapid growth of population, agriculture, commerce, and manufacturing, as well as the neutral stance maintained by the United States amid conflicts in Europe.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He attributed the country's success to the stability provided by its Constitution and encouraged Congress to continue to nurture the nation's advantages.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] The president also acknowledged the resolution of the Whiskey Rebellion and noted that the misled citizens had returned to lawfulness, allowing him to extend pardons to those involved.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He emphasized the need for military and militia reform to ensure national security and the continued protection of frontier inhabitants from lawless attacks against Native Americans.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] The **1796 State of the Union Address** was given by George Washington, the first president of the United States, on Wednesday, December 7, 1796.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] It was given in Congress Hall, Philadelphia.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] The President also noted negotiations with the Creek Nation regarding purchase of land, which had stalled at that time.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] The President also recommended the establishment of an official military academy noting that a nation should "never be without an adequate stock of military knowledge for emergencies".
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] The **1797 State of the Union Address** was delivered by John Adams, second president of the United States, on Wednesday, November 22, 1797, in the Congress Hall of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] At the time of the address, sickness was spreading through Philadelphia and Adams notes in his introduction that he was tempted to relocate the assembly of the national legislature but avoided this due to inevitable expense and general inconvenience.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] Adams began his State of the Union Address by expressing concern over European, most notably French, aggression towards American merchant vessels.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] He emphasizes the importance of America's growing role in international commerce, citing accomplishments in agriculture and commercial fishing.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] In July and August 1797 delegates traveled to the Batavian Republic and then to France.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] They arrived in Paris on September 19 and began negotiations in the hope of pacifying Franco-American relations.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the speech was delivered, the status of the meetings in France were unknown, but Adams knew and stated in the speech that war, with France or possibly other European countries, for example Great Britain, was becoming an increasingly likely turn of events.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] The Federalist Party advocated going to war, but Adams ignored Francophobia and avoided going to war with France until 1798 in the Quasi-War.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] The U.S. later went to war with Britain in the War of 1812, partly due to Jefferson's refusal to pay tribute to a foreign nation.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] Adams' assertion that "respect to treaties has been so diminished" is a reference to the violation of the Treaty of Alliance by the French through piracy and the violation of Pinckney's Treaty by the Spanish through illegal garrisons in the western U.S. frontiers.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] Although these treaties were highly unfavorable to the U.S., the policy of appeasement carried out during the Washington and Adams administrations was necessary to provide time for the U.S. to build up its navy and militia.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] Foreign intervention in domestic affairs of the U.S. was not limited to abuses in the water.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] Adams condemned ventures by foreign agents, such as those of Spain, who tried to incite an insurgency among Native Americans.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] Adams expresses hope that the as yet unfulfilled obligations of the Treaty of Amity and Commerce (1797), surveying the St.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] Adams directly addresses the House of Representatives in regard to the national debt and taxes which had to be raised in order to fund a larger, more mobile Army.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] He warns against loans as he believed that they had contributed to the vast debt and economic collapse of historical empires.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1797-state-of-the-union-address] He ends his address by reiterating his general theme of the necessity to militarize to adequately defend against foreign imperialism.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] The **1847 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the 11th president of the United States James K.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] Polk to the 30th United States Congress on December 7, 1847.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] President Polk addressed issues of national prosperity, the ongoing Mexican-American War, and the growth of American territorial interests.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] The Mexican-American War was a central focus of the address.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] Polk detailed the events leading to war, emphasizing that "the United States were the aggrieved nation" forced into conflict after Mexico's refusal to negotiate.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] He justified the need for territorial indemnity, stressing that the United States sought compensation for the costs of war and reparations for longstanding grievances with Mexico, as well as the establishment of secure borders along the Rio Grande.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] Polk also addressed concerns over territorial expansion, particularly the acquisition of New Mexico and California.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] He argued that Mexico could neither govern nor defend these distant regions effectively and claimed they were “naturally connected” to the U.S.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] He anticipated that under American governance, these territories would develop rapidly, providing secure access to the Pacific and offering new commercial opportunities with East Asia.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] Citing the need for improved governance in the recently acquired Oregon Territory, Polk proposed the establishment of a territorial government and encouraged settlement, recommending land grants as incentives to pioneers moving westward.
[src:1847-state-of-the-union-address/1847-state-of-the-union-address] He also reaffirmed America's commitment to westward expansion, framing it as vital for both economic growth and national security.
